description.text: These are the plastic parts needed to build a wind vane. When used with a Yocto-Knob this thing will give you wind direction through USB.

These are plastic parts needed to build an USB wind vane. They are meant to be used with a Yocto-Knob ( yoctopuce.com/EN/products/usb-sensors/yocto-knob ), but any electronics with GPIO, such as Raspberry PI or Arduino, would probably do as well. You will find here instructions for assembly. Details about electronics and programming can be found on our blog: yoctopuce.com/EN/article/how-to-measure-wind-part-2 This thing is assembled using screws and brass threaded inserts. This allows to assemble and disassemble it quickly and easily. Moreover, the final assembly is rock solid. Additional Hardware
You will need some non-printable hardware to build this thing.
  • Five 3mm LEDs as powerful as possible, e.g. L-7104SEC-J3 from Kingbright
  • Five 3mm photo-transistors, e.g. : SFH 310-2/3 from OSRAM
  • Five 200 Î© resistors
  • Non insulated wire
  • Electric wire
  • A Yocto-Knob or equivalent
  • A 3mm axle
  • Two 3x10x4 stainless bearing ex: xirosÂ® B180 from igus.com
  • M3 threaded inserts, such as BN 1036 - DIN 16903 B from bossard.com
  • M3 screws
  • M3 headless screws
  • Some 13x3 metallic washers
  • Some glue suited for the matter used by your 3D printer (*)
  • Optionally, a 16mm rod and a PG.M0.7GL.LN connector from LEMO.
    • (*) If you are using ABS, you may want to try Methyl-Ethyl-Ketone (MEK). Actually it's not glue but a powerful ABS solvent allowing to literally weld parts. Tools
  • Glue gun
  • Fine wire cutter
  • A pair of tweezers
  • Various screw drivers
  • Solder iron
    • Mounting steps
    STEP 1
    Make rings with the non-insulated wire. Solder the rings, the phototransistors and electric wire together in one led-holder, then do the same with the led and resistors in the second led-holder. This is delicate work, fine wire cutter and a pair of tweezers will help. Once both are working, fill the voids with hot glue. STEP 2
    Place the threaded inserts with a solder iron in all the body and the hub parts STEP 3
    Stack the body bottom, the led holder with the leds. Place one bearings. Force the wheel on the axle and place it. STEP 4
    Stack the body and the led holder with the photo-transistors, place the second bearing in the top body and close the body. The axle must spin freely. If needed, use washers. STEP 5
    Glue the the rod parts and the stabilizer. You can place toothpick in the holes for proper alignment. STEP 6
    Place a threaded insert on the rod end, place the nose ring, and screw as many metallic washers as needed for a proper balance. Force the nose on head of the screw fixing the ballast. Install the rod between the two hub parts. Notice the headless screws used to lock it on the axle. You can make spacers from a brass 3mm tube, and force them into to the hub parts to make sure plastic wont bend when you tighten the headless screws. STEP 7
    Assemble the body and the rotor. Optionally you can use the support. The support is designed to mount the wind vane on a 16mm rod and connect it with a PG.M0.7GL.LN connector Assembly is complete, now you need to wire it and to write the program needed to decode the axle positions. For more info on the electronics, see yoctopuce.com/EN/article/how-to-measure-wind-part-2

title: Printable Filament Stand
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: I liked the printable filament spindle idea but did not have easy access to a lazy Susan and thought a vertical version would work better anyways.  I have been using for a few weeks now.  Sorry for the delay in putting up.

1) Print the botom half of the printable filament spindle twice(don't print top half), and the locking brackets, and cross bars.
2) Print 4 spinner.stl
3) print 2 stand top.stl
4) print 4 stand bottom.stl
5) Cut 6 small pieces of filament off(10 to 20mm in length) 6) Assemble and glue the first half of the spindle togehter.
7) Assemble and glue the second half of the spindle together.
8) place the pointy end of the cross beams in each of the large pieces(this will take some force)
9) glue the ends of the cross beams that are not presure fitted into the holes on the other half(this is so we can take the filament apart to add plastic but it will want to hold itself together)
10) place each set of the spinners together to make an X and fit a skeatboard bearing into the hole.
11) Place a 5/16th rod(7.9mm) through each of the ball bearings and line the 2 spinners up with each side of the spindle.
12) glue the spindles in place.
13) place the short filament pieces into 1 side of the stand bottom(helps if you sharpen the tips a little and use pliers to push in)
14) place the other side of the short filament pieces into the other stand bottom and glue together
15) glue the stand top on to the 2 stand bottoms
16) place the rod and spindle into the 2 stands

title: Holder for Nexa Remote Switch system.

description.text:
This is a wall holder for the remote of the Nexa PE-3 (I think that's what's it's called) wireless switch pack. It is for the rounded remote in the pic, older ones are more square, there are also bigger ones with more buttons by the same manufacturer.   
It is a wireless system for switching on and off anything connected to a socket, it is sold mostly in Scandinavia and the UK I think. If you have a Clas-Ohlson store nearby then they have it. Usually sold in a pack of 3x switches and a remote.  
I needed one and made one, so why not upload it and share? :-)

There are two files. The one with "CS" in the name has counter sunk screw holes. The screw I used was 4x small 8mm wood screw with a 5mm diameter top.
The "SH" one is just with straight 2mm holes for those who would like to drill their own screw sinks, to fit whatever screws you have laying around. Just use more than two layers and the slicer should pack alot of plastic around the holes, giving you some leeway to drill. It's not like this thing uses alot of plastic anyways, so might as well crank up the layering. The screws should not stick out since this is a tight fit. There is a 1 degree slip angle on this so the unit slides nicely in and out, but still a tight fit. Scale ever so slightly if your printer gives you any weirdness.
Thingiverse seems to insist on kicking my things over on their side in the preview. I printed this standing upright since that gave the best look. Layering direction is not really an issue here since this thing is not subject to rough handling (Unless you have kids or something).
Took around 40 mins to print with 0,2mm layer resolution. I did use supports just to be safe. But might print fine without it.

description.text:
Home Depot used to sell this neat modular shelving system called "Peg-Lok".  It consisted of various pre-cut boards held together with press-fit pegs that could be combined in a variety of ways to make linked shelving units.  After recently moving across country, I sadly discovered that all my Peg-Lok pegs had been lost.  Fortunately, there was one loose peg in a box, which provided the template to design a replacement.
If you have access to a decent saw and jig for cutting angles, you can easily make these tapered pegs by cutting 7/8" dowels into 1.5" long segments, then cutting diagonally across the segments at a 10 degree angle.  However, if you have a 3D printer and no wood tools, this model is for you!

• Lose your Peg-Lok pegs.
  • Print attached STL file.
  • If you need more pegs, goto 2. (If you have an automated build platform, tell it to goto 2 while you goto lunch.)

Made in June 2012 - cute lil mushroom toy figurines in three body types! :)

The concept was created when I was considering going to Toronto's Fan Expo as a vendor and I wanted to create something that fit within that vibe. .
But I really wanted to capture the geek/nerd essence. I thought ... who would stand out in a crowd of people who already embraced geekdom? And I thought ... you know, that guy who goes to a costume party as a potatoe .. or that girl who dresses like a cardboard box - instead of the TV character, comic hero.
.
So the Fan Shrooms were born, with the thought to extend into other vegetables or off beat things.

title: Filament cleaner for Velleman K8200 3D printer

description.text:
People on different forums reported problems with clogged nozzle. One of the reasons may be a dust, powder or some other contamination on the filament. I have thought, it would be nice to have a little cleaner before the extruder…
I designed it in the way that it can be easily mounted on the frame using one of my clips (FULL http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:221362 or FLAT http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:225642) and 2 pins.
It can be moved left or right along the frame or rotated to put it in optimal position for the filament to go through. I cut a small piece of a kitchen sponge – it does the job. The only thing worth of considerations is that the material used to clean the filament is soft when it is dry as it needs to hold the filament tight – some of the sponges are rock hard when dry (will not surround the filament snugly enough) and get softer only when wet. More details, the source code, schematic, part list can be found on my blog: http://ljwinkler.blogspot.com/2014/08/filament-cleaner-for-velleman-k8200-3d.html Cheers,
LJ

author: Jo3co15

description.text:
This is the third version of my universal filament coaster caddy that works like reverse skates (you can simply skip printing version 1-2, they're just there for keepsakes). They're headache free as the design is for poorly calibrated and small 3d printers. You just print 4 of them and then snap in the 4 608z bearings. Since both "skates" are self correcting, you just place them on the edges of any spool and it'll work smoothly. You don't even need any tools to put them together, and printing them in hexagon is strong enough for most spools, no need for solid infills or isolinear builds like most other caddies.
Furthermore the latest version 3 includes a guide to center spools onto the bearings. It featured minimalized filament usage and the legs have been reduced to thin versions on the edges to help with balance and prevent the feet from flipping over. If you have poster putty, I recommend using a little bit of that to ensure the filament caddy doesn't shift or putting them on a non-slip surface.

title: Springy Clip Case for iPhone 5c ver2

description.text:
Version 2: Due to body and processor heat, PLA would soften and allow the clip to fall out. New retaining wings prevent that.
This is a case for an iPhone 5c, with a pocket (or money) clip. Due to the bendyness of PLA, the clip, as seen in the pictures, is effectively spring-loaded when installed.
The case itself will work without the clip, and is based on the iPhone 5c case by Cleven at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:268940.

Print at .2 height to eliminate curling, Infill is probably better the higher you go, to prevent the walls of the clip and the case from delaminating:
Suggested:
2 shells
0.2mm height
15-50% infill. Standard PLA print for everything else.
This was not tested in ABS, but it should work for that, too.
When parts are in-hand:
BEFORE INSERTING PHONE: Insert curly end of clip into slot to make pointy end flush on the inside. Push on the clip from the inside of the case, and insert the mushroom-looking pin into the triangle void at the top. Cram it in there until flush with the pin.
As Cleven says, really cram your phone up in there, because it will take some force and will not want to come out.

This is an initial version of my idea for a replacement Cupcake xy carriage assembly. It's designed to duplicate the functionality of a ABP, but incorporating the conveyor belt directly into the y stage. I wanted an ABP but didn't want to replace my existing electronics and HBP with new parts (at $185). I decided that the ideal setup would be to use existing Makerbot parts to create it. Instead of having the stepper move the platform and use a different motor to drive the conveyor belt, this is designed to have the y axis stepper move the CONVEYOR BELT during the build, with the HBP moving only in the x axis underneath it. When done, the end.gcode can just move the y axis to +200 to drop the piece off the front of the belt. It has ball bearing movements and the carriage is about 15mm shorter than a normal Cupcake, providing for taller builds. It steals parts from a Mendel (eight 624 bearings and a modified version of the 180 and 360 sleds), and it has been designed to cannibalize most parts from the existing Cupcake x and y stages (hence, the name). It uses an HBP only modified with countersunk boltheads for a flat surface and the carriage gets stability by utilizing the old y-stage guide rods as support beams that the printed parts attach to. The entire bed has four leveling screws, and the HBP has leveling screws on spring loaded floats, similar to a Mendel bed. The conveyor belt is driven with 5 drive rollers, one of which has tensioner adjustments to keep the belt tight and running straight. The various printed parts are held together with dovetail joinery, which I've used with success on other projects to make strong hardwareless connections (they can be glued together with ABS glue if more strength is needed, but I haven't had to before). Unfortunately, this is in a beta stage at this point, but I'm posting it to meet the deadline for the bearing contest. I've printed most parts, but I messed up on the length of my HBP springs and the x-belt clamp, which I need to redesign (and aren't depicted in the renderings). I've made my conveyor (out of .0002 PET which I bought before MBI spec'd it at .0005) and the roller assemblies (I found 3/8"latex tubing which is super-sticky and fits on 1/4" rod at my local home store). I have to go to work today though, so I'll be putting it together over the next few days and work out any kinks. Anyway, I created the models in OpenSCAD and designed them to be parametric, using a variety of bearing sizes or whatever thicknesses of rollers that you source at home. I'll clean up the SCADs and post them within the week. UPDATE - Don't build it in this state. I put one together and it has several strength-related issues. I'm working on v3, which is a complete redesign. I'm still hopeful it will work with modification, but I cannot recommend it at this point.

I'll post detailed instructions when I get finished making my working copy, but until then:
Print the parts.  There are some small details and 45 degree overhangs, but with care, even a moderately-tuned bot can produce workable copies.  You will have to drill and clean out the holes.  
Assemble 5 rollers (per ABP instructions), with 120mm rod and 100mm tubing (except for the geared drive roller that has an additional 20mm extension for the gear on one side).  Just cut the rod (I used aluminum) and make sure you sand and bevel the ends smooth.
Your PET belt can be sized to length when you finish the build, but it's 100mm wide and prepared like the ABP belt.  McMaster-Carr sells a lifetime supply (25' long roll) for about $10.
Assemble the dovetailed pieces (refer to the whole-carriage rendering for details), with the rollers inserted.  Trim as little of the dovetails as possible, because they should be a tight fit (the layered ridges help hold them together better too!)  
The bearing assemblies all go together like a Mendel (same order of washers, bearings, and nut.  The lower sleds have 6mm holes through them to accept the old y-stage guide rods as skeletal pieces of the new carriage.  They're secured with M3 bolts through the rod clamps on the x360 and rear sled pieces.
The levelers use an M3 bolt and 3 nuts.  The upper cutout for each leveler (on the sides of the bed) is for two nuts screwed together under tension (locking them into position on the bolt) which provide a bearing surface for the bolt to rotate freely in the cutout (they are a bit of a pain to assemble because they have to be tightened together inside the cutout.  Sorry.  If anyone has a slicker setup, please let me know).  The lower cutouts (on the sled risers) is for a trapped nut.  As the cap bolt is turned it will raise and lower the bed (I'll provide photos soon).
The HBP is mounted sideways, floating on printed springs held by M3 bolts (which perform double duty, also connecting the three sections of the bed together).
The gears are printed, using Nophead-style trapped nuts to screw the gear to the motor and drive roller.
After assembly, it should, with luck, be a drop in replacement for the old bed.  The machines.xml will need to be altered to recalibrate the y movements.  After I test it, I'll post the new machine.xml specs, and will probably alter the gear stls to get a ratio that is closer to the existing specs.
